# User Stories — NBA Stats Explorer

**Product:** NBA Stats Explorer  
**Version:** 1.0  
**Date:** June 2026  

---

## How to Read This Document

Each story follows the format:

> **As a** [persona], **I want to** [action], **so that** [outcome].

Stories are grouped by feature area and ordered by priority (P0 = must have, P1 = should have, P2 = nice to have). Each story includes acceptance criteria and, where relevant, edge cases.

---

## Epic 1 — API Key Setup

### US-001 · Enter API key
**Priority:** P0

> As a user, I want to paste my balldontlie.io API key into the app, so that I can authenticate my requests and access NBA data.

**Acceptance criteria:**
- [ ] An API key input field is visible on first load, before any data is fetched.
- [ ] The field accepts a text string and masks it as a password field for security.
- [ ] When a valid key is entered, the status badge changes to "connected" after the first successful API call.
- [ ] The app never sends the key to any server other than `api.balldontlie.io`.

**Edge cases:**
- If the key is invalid, the badge shows "error" and an inline message asks the user to check the key.
- If no key is present and a search is triggered, a prompt directs the user to add one.

---

### US-002 · See connection status
**Priority:** P0

> As a user, I want to see whether my API key is working, so that I can quickly diagnose connection problems without guessing.

**Acceptance criteria:**
- [ ] Status badge shows one of three states: "not set" (grey), "connected" (green), "error" (red).
- [ ] Status updates automatically after each API response.
- [ ] The badge is visible at all times, not hidden behind a settings menu.

